{
  "The four types of suborbitals are:": "",
  "1, 2, 3, 4": "",
  "a, b, c, d": "",
  "s, p, d, f": "",
  "w, x, y, z": "",
  "The four sublevel types are s (sharp), p (principal), d (diffuse), and f (fundamental). These names originated from spectroscopic observations of emission lines.": "",
  "How many electrons can the s suborbital hold?": "",
  "10": "",
  "2": "",
  "14": "",
  "6": "",
  "The s sublevel has 1 orbital that holds a maximum of 2 electrons (with opposite spins, per the Pauli exclusion principle). Every energy level has an s sublevel.": "",
  "How many electrons can the p suborbital hold?": "",
  "The p sublevel has 3 orbitals (px, py, pz), each holding 2 electrons, for a total of 6. The p sublevel first appears at energy level 2.": "",
  "How many electrons can the d suborbital hold?": "",
  "The d sublevel has 5 orbitals, each holding 2 electrons, for a total of 10. The d sublevel is responsible for the properties of transition metals.": "",
  "How many electrons can the f suborbital hold?": "",
  "The f sublevel has 7 orbitals, each holding 2 electrons, for a total of 14. The f sublevel is filled by lanthanides and actinides.": "",
  "The d suborbital first appears at energy level:": "",
  "3": "",
  "4": "",
  "1": "",
  "The d sublevel first appears at n=3, but due to the Aufbau principle, 3d is higher in energy than 4s. So electrons fill 4s before 3d — this is why transition metals start in Period 4.": "",
  "The f suborbital first appears at energy level:": "",
  "5": "",
  "The f sublevel first appears at n=4. The 4f electrons are filled by the lanthanides (elements 57-71), and 5f by the actinides (elements 89-103).": "",
  "How many orbitals does the p sublevel contain?": "",
  "7": "",
  "The p sublevel has 3 orbitals oriented along the x, y, and z axes. Each orbital holds 2 electrons, giving p a maximum capacity of 6 electrons.": "",
  "How many orbitals does the d sublevel contain?": "",
  "The d sublevel has 5 orbitals (dxy, dxz, dyz, dx²-y², dz²). Each holds 2 electrons for a total of 10. The partially filled d orbitals give transition metals their unique properties.": "",
  "The maximum number of electrons in any single orbital is:": "",
  "8": "",
  "The Pauli exclusion principle states each orbital holds at most 2 electrons, which must have opposite spins (spin-up and spin-down). This applies to all orbital types.": "",
  "What is a sublevel (subshell)?": "",
  "A subdivision within an energy level that contains orbitals of a specific type (s, p, d, or f)": "",
  "Another name for the nucleus that houses the protons and neutrons at the center of the atom": "",
  "A type of chemical bond formed between two atoms sharing their outermost valence electrons": "",
  "The space between atoms in a crystal lattice where electrons cannot exist at any energy": "",
  "Energy levels (n=1, 2, 3...) are divided into sublevels. The number of sublevels equals the principal quantum number: n=1 has only s; n=2 has s and p; n=3 has s, p, and d; n=4 has s, p, d, and f.": "",
  "What is an orbital?": "",
  "A type of chemical bond": "",
  "A fixed circular path an electron follows": "",
  "A region of space where there is a high probability of finding an electron": "",
  "The nucleus of an atom": "",
  "Unlike Bohr's circular orbits, orbitals are three-dimensional probability clouds. An orbital describes where an electron is likely (about 90% probability) to be found, not a definite path.": "",
  "What is the Aufbau principle?": "",
  "All orbitals fill simultaneously": "",
  "Electrons fill the highest-energy orbitals first": "",
  "Electrons fill the lowest-energy orbitals first before moving to higher-energy ones": "",
  "Electrons only fill s orbitals": "",
  "'Aufbau' is German for 'building up.' Electrons fill in the order: 1s → 2s → 2p → 3s → 3p → 4s → 3d → 4p → 5s → 4d... The diagonal rule helps remember this sequence.": "",
  "What is the Pauli exclusion principle?": "",
  "No two electrons in an atom can have all four quantum numbers identical — max 2 per orbital with opposite spins": "",
  "Protons and electrons must be equal": "",
  "Orbitals can hold unlimited electrons": "",
  "Electrons always pair before filling new orbitals": "",
  "Wolfgang Pauli's principle limits each orbital to 2 electrons with opposite spins (+½ and -½). This is why s holds 2, p holds 6 (3×2), d holds 10 (5×2), and f holds 14 (7×2).": "",
  "What is Hund's rule?": "",
  "Electrons always pair up immediately": "",
  "Electrons fill degenerate orbitals (same energy) singly with parallel spins before pairing up": "",
  "All orbitals must be empty before filling": "",
  "Electrons alternate between s and p": "",
  "Think of Hund's rule like bus seating: passengers sit alone before doubling up. In the 2p sublevel with 3 orbitals, the first 3 electrons each go into separate orbitals before any pairing occurs.": "",
  "What is the principal quantum number (n)?": "",
  "The number that indicates the main energy level and size of an orbital (n = 1, 2, 3...)": "",
  "The shape of the orbital determined by the angular momentum quantum number (l = 0, 1, 2...)": "",
  "The spin of an electron within an orbital that determines its magnetic orientation (ms = +½, -½)": "",
  "The number of protons in an atom that defines which element it is on the periodic table": "",
  "The principal quantum number n determines the energy level and approximate distance from the nucleus. As n increases, orbitals get larger, and the electron has more energy.": "",
  "What is a degenerate orbital?": "",
  "Orbitals that have the same energy level within a sublevel (e.g., the three 2p orbitals)": "",
  "Orbitals located in the nucleus that house protons and determine the atom's overall charge": "",
  "Orbitals that have lost their electrons through ionization and now exist in an excited state": "",
  "Orbitals that overlap between two bonded atoms to form sigma or pi molecular bonds": "",
  "The three p orbitals (px, py, pz) in the same shell all have equal energy — they are degenerate. Hund's rule applies to degenerate orbitals: fill each singly before pairing.": "",
  "The total number of orbitals in an energy level n equals:": "",
  "2n": "",
  "n × 2": "",
  "n + 1": "",
  "n²": "",
  "Energy level n has n² orbitals: n=1 has 1 (s), n=2 has 4 (1s + 3p), n=3 has 9 (1s + 3p + 5d), n=4 has 16 (1s + 3p + 5d + 7f). Maximum electrons = 2n².": "",
  "What is the diagonal rule used for?": "",
  "Drawing Lewis structures": "",
  "Determining the order in which orbitals are filled with electrons": "",
  "Finding the number of neutrons": "",
  "Calculating atomic mass": "",
  "The diagonal rule (or Madelung's rule) gives the filling order: 1s, 2s, 2p, 3s, 3p, 4s, 3d, 4p, 5s, 4d, 5p, 6s, 4f... Notice that 4s fills before 3d because 4s is lower in energy.": "",
  "How many sublevels does energy level n=3 have?": "",
  "1 (s only)": "",
  "4 (s, p, d, f)": "",
  "2 (s, p)": "",
  "3 (s, p, d)": "",
  "Energy level n has n types of sublevels. So n=3 has 3 sublevels: 3s (2e), 3p (6e), and 3d (10e), holding a maximum of 18 electrons total.": "",
  "A student asks why transition metals like iron can form multiple ions (Fe²⁺ and Fe³⁺). The answer relates to:": "",
  "Iron only has s electrons in its outer shell, which limits how many bonds it can form": "",
  "Iron has 2 nuclei that can each release different numbers of protons during reactions": "",
  "Iron is a noble gas with a completely filled outer shell, so it rarely forms any ions": "",
  "The 3d and 4s sublevels are close in energy, so varying numbers of electrons can be lost": "",
  "Iron's configuration is [Ar] 3d⁶ 4s². Since 3d and 4s are close in energy, iron can lose 2 electrons (Fe²⁺: lose 4s²) or 3 electrons (Fe³⁺: lose 4s² and one 3d). This versatility is characteristic of d-block elements.": "",
  "Neon lights produce different colors from different noble gases. The colors are determined by:": "",
  "The number of neutrons in each gas, which determines the mass and controls the color of light emitted": "",
  "The temperature of the gas inside the tube, which shifts the frequency of thermal radiation produced": "",
  "Chemical reactions between the gases that produce new colored compounds through molecular rearrangement": "",
  "Electrons jumping between specific suborbital energy levels and releasing photons of characteristic wavelengths": "",
  "When electrons are excited by electricity, they jump to higher suborbital energy levels. When they fall back down, they emit photons. The specific energy gaps between sublevels determine the wavelength (color) of light.": "",
  "A chemistry teacher explains why 4s fills before 3d even though 4 > 3. The reason is:": "",
  "The 3d sublevel doesn't exist for potassium because it only forms at higher atomic numbers": "",
  "The 4s orbital can hold more electrons than 3d, so nature fills the larger orbital first": "",
  "Electrons prefer larger orbitals because there is less electron-electron repulsion in them": "",
  "The 4s orbital is lower in energy than 3d due to its deeper penetration toward the nucleus": "",
  "The 4s orbital penetrates closer to the nucleus than 3d, giving it lower average energy. The Aufbau principle dictates filling 4s before 3d. However, when ionized, transition metals lose 4s electrons first.": "",
  "Lanthanides and actinides are placed at the bottom of the periodic table. Their special position is because they are filling:": "",
  "The f suborbital, which holds up to 14 electrons": "",
  "The s suborbital": "",
  "No suborbitals — they are exceptions": "",
  "The p suborbital": "",
  "Lanthanides fill the 4f sublevel (14 electrons) and actinides fill the 5f sublevel. Placing them in the main table would make it 32 columns wide, so they're displayed separately for compactness.": "",
  "Silicon's semiconductor properties make it essential for computer chips. Its electron configuration involves:": "",
  "No valence electrons exist in silicon's outer shell, which is why it acts as a perfect insulator always": "",
  "Both s and p sublevels (1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s² 3p²), with partially filled 3p providing semiconductor behavior": "",
  "Only d sublevels are occupied in silicon's configuration, giving it transition metal-like properties": "",
  "Only f sublevels are filled in silicon's electron arrangement, similar to the lanthanide elements": "",
  "Silicon (Z=14) has 4 valence electrons in s and p sublevels. The partially filled 3p orbital creates a band gap that allows silicon to conduct electricity under certain conditions — perfect for transistors.": "",
  "An MRI machine uses a strong magnet. Many transition metals are magnetic because:": "",
  "All metals are equally magnetic because their nuclei generate uniform electromagnetic fields": "",
  "They have no electrons in their outer shells, which allows the nucleus to project magnetism": "",
  "Their s orbitals produce magnetism by oscillating rapidly between energy levels in the atom": "",
  "Their partially filled d sublevels contain unpaired electrons that create magnetic moments": "",
  "Unpaired electrons in d orbitals act like tiny magnets. Iron (3d⁶) has 4 unpaired d electrons, making it strongly ferromagnetic. Fully paired electrons cancel out, so metals with full d sublevels are not magnetic.": "",
  "A student asks why helium (He) is in Group 18 (noble gases) even though its electrons are in the 1s suborbital. The reason is:": "",
  "Helium is a mistake on the periodic table and should be placed in Group 2 with the alkaline metals": "",
  "Helium has 8 electrons in its outer shell, satisfying the octet rule like all other noble gases": "",
  "Helium's 1s² is a full outer shell, giving it noble gas stability like other Group 18 elements": "",
  "Helium has d orbitals that are completely filled, giving it the same stability as the heavier nobles": "",
  "Although helium has only 2 electrons (1s²), its first shell is completely full. A complete outer shell = maximum stability = noble gas behavior. The 1s shell can only hold 2 electrons, so the duet rule applies.": "",
  "Copper's actual electron configuration is [Ar] 3d¹⁰ 4s¹ instead of the expected [Ar] 3d⁹ 4s². This exception occurs because:": "",
  "A completely filled d sublevel (3d¹⁰) provides extra stability, so one 4s electron shifts to 3d": "",
  "Copper has 30 protons but 29 electrons": "",
  "The Aufbau principle does not apply to copper": "",
  "Copper is not a real element": "",
  "Half-filled and fully filled d sublevels are exceptionally stable due to electron exchange energy. Copper 'borrows' one 4s electron to achieve the favorable 3d¹⁰ configuration. Chromium ([Ar] 3d⁵ 4s¹) is another famous exception.": "",
  "Fireworks produce colors because metal salts are heated. From a suborbital perspective, what happens?": "",
  "The metals melt inside the firework and the molten metal changes color based on its melting point": "",
  "Protons absorb all the incoming light and re-emit it at different wavelengths based on nuclear size": "",
  "Neutrons produce the light by decaying radioactively and releasing gamma photons as visible colors": "",
  "Heat excites electrons to higher sublevels; as they fall back, they release energy as colored light": "",
  "Each metal has unique energy gaps between sublevels. When excited electrons drop from a higher sublevel to a lower one, they emit photons of specific wavelengths: strontium (red), barium (green), copper (blue).": "",
  "A researcher studying rare earth elements notes that cerium (Ce) and neodymium (Nd) have similar properties despite different electron counts. This similarity occurs because:": "",
  "They are the same element with different isotopes, which is why their chemical properties appear identical": "",
  "Both are lanthanides filling the 4f sublevel, which is deeply buried and doesn't significantly affect chemistry": "",
  "They have identical electron configurations in every sublevel, resulting in perfectly matching properties": "",
  "They have no f electrons at all and rely solely on their d sublevels to determine chemical behavior": "",
  "The 4f sublevel is shielded by 5s, 5p, and other outer electrons. Since f electrons are buried deep within the atom, they don't directly participate in bonding, making lanthanides chemically very similar to each other.": ""
}